{
  "query": "What is the single most important conservation action for the monarch butterfly?",
  "relevant_summary": "Based on the evidence from action documents, planting parks, gardens and road verges with appropriate native species appears to be the most important conservation action for monarch butterflies (Action 3842). This action specifically shows benefits for monarch butterflies through studies demonstrating that when taller native milkweed species were planted, they had a higher abundance of monarch butterfly eggs and caterpillars than shorter milkweed species. Additionally, monarch butterfly adults used common milkweed planted in gardens more than milkweed planted in meadows, and the survival of monarch butterfly caterpillars was similar on common milkweed planted in gardens and meadows. The growth of monarch butterfly caterpillars was also similar on eight different native milkweed species (Action 3842). Other relevant actions include replanting native vegetation, which showed that common milkweed planted in meadows supported monarch butterfly eggs and had similar survival rates for monarch butterfly eggs and caterpillars in meadows or private gardens (Action 3933). Captive rearing has also been successful for monarch butterflies, with one study reporting that monarch butterfly populations were successfully reared in captivity for multiple generations, and monarch caterpillars showed different survival rates when reared on different species of milkweed (Action 3916).",
